s]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Pennyframstad", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed wiki link in lead in", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georg_Brandl_Egloff"}
{"title_page": "Saint Nuri", "text_new": "{{Infobox saint\n| name            = Saint Nuri\n| image           = \n| imagesize       = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| titles          = Mystic\n| birth_date      = c. 840 C.E.\n| birth_place     = [[Baghdad]]\n| death_date      = c. 908 C.E.\n| death_place     = [[Baghdad]] \n| venerated_in    = [[Islam]], [[Sunni]]\n| influences      = [[Muhammad]]\n| major_works   = ''Stations of the Hearts''\n}}\n{{Sufism|Notable early}}\n'''Ahmed Ibn Abu al-Hussain al-Nuri''' ({{lang-fa|\u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u06cc\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0648\u0631\u06cc}}) (died 908 AD), known also as '''Nuri''', was a famous early [[Sufi]] [[saint]].<ref>Carl W. Ernst, \"Words of ectasy in Sufism\", SUNY Press, 1985.  pg 97: \"A Sufi of Iranian origin (d. 907) was one of the most eminent mystics of Baghdad</ref> He was of [[Persian people|Persian]] origins, but born in [[Baghdad]] in 840 CE where spent most of his life.<ref>N. Hanif, ''Biographical encyclopaedia of Sufis: Central Asia and Middle East'', p. 368</ref> He is the author of ''Maqamat al-qulub'' (''Stations of the Hearts''). He is famous for saying, \"I love God and God loves me\".<ref>Al-Sarraj, Pages From the \"Kitab al-Luma' , ed. AJ. Arberry (London: Luzac, 1947), p. 5</ref> He is one of the earliest Sufis who was clearly mystical as illustrated by his saying \"Joining with the Truth is parting from everything else, as parting with everything else is joining with it\"<ref>Al-Sulami, Tabaqat, 153 = Sh., 166</ref>\n\nNuri and several of his friends were accused of heresy and charged in 878 C.E. Nuri offered to be tried before his companions.  The regent at the time was impressed by such magnanimity and investigated the case and found these Sufis to be good Muslims.  Thus he set the accused free. Nuri, however, was exiled to [[Raqqa]] in [[Syria]], whence he returned some years later, much deteriorated physically.<ref>Carl W. Ernst, \"Words of ectasy in Sufism\", SUNY Press, 1985.  pg 98</ref>\n\nPoetry and statements from Nuri are narrated in popular Sufism.  According to popular accounts, he gained the title \"Nuri\" because he \"radiated light when talking\".  He was acquainted with [[Junayd Baghdadi]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* [[Christopher Melchert]]: [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1595736 ''The Transition from Ascetism to Mysticism at the Middle of the Ninth Century''], in: Studia Islamica 83 (1996), 51\u201370.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.luckynmalone.co.uk/sufism/ Nuri Bibliography]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nuri, Saint}}\n[[Category:Iraqi Sufis]]\n[[Category:Iraqi Sufi saints]]\n[[Category:840 births]]\n[[Category:907 deaths]]\n\n\n{{Sufism-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox saint\n| name            = Saint Nuri\n| image           = \n| imagesize       = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| titles          = Mystic\n| birth_date      = c. 840 C.E.\n| birth_place     = [[Baghdad]]\n| death_date      = c. 908 C.E.\n| death_place     = [[Baghdad]] \n| venerated_in    = [[Islam]], [[Sunni]]\n| influences      = [[Muhammad]]\n| major_works   = ''Stations of the Hearts''\n}}\n{{Sufism|Notable early}}\n'''Ahmed Ibn Abu al-Hussain al-Nuri''' ({{lang-fa|\u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u06cc\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0648\u0631\u06cc}}) (died 908 AD), known also as '''Nuri''', was a famous early [[Sufi]] [[saint]].<ref>Carl W. Ernst, \"Words of ectasy in Sufism\", SUNY Press, 1985.  pg 97: \"A Sufi of Iranian origin (d. 907) was one of the most eminent mystics of Baghdad</ref> He was of [[Persian people|Persian]] origins, but born in [[Baghdad]] in 840 CE where spent most of his life.<ref>N. Hanif, ''Biographical encyclopaedia of Sufis: Central Asia and Middle East'', p. 368</ref> He is the author of ''Maqamat al-qulub'' (''Stations of the Hearts''). He is famous for saying, \"I love God and God loves me\".<ref>Al-Sarraj, Pages From the \"Kitab al-Luma' , ed. AJ. Arberry (London: Luzac, 1947), p. 5</ref> He is one of the earliest Sufis who was clearly mystical as illustrated by his saying \"Joining with the Truth is parting from everything else, as parting with everything else is joining with it\"<ref>Al-Sulami, Tabaqat, 153 = Sh., 166</ref>\n\nNuri and several of his friends were accused of heresy and charged in 878 C.E. Nuri offered to be tried before his companions.  The regent at the time was impressed by such magnanimity and investigated the case and found these Sufis to be good Muslims.  Thus he set the accused free. Nuri, however, was exiled to [[Raqqa]] in [[Syria]], whence he returned some years later, much deteriorated physically.<ref>Carl W. Ernst, \"Words of ectasy in Sufism\", SUNY Press, 1985.  pg 98</ref>\n\nPoetry and statements from Nuri are narrated in popular Sufism.  According to popular accounts, he gained the title \"Nuri\" because he \"radiated light when talking\".  He was acquainted with [[Junayd Baghdadi]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* [[Christopher Melchert]]: [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1595736 ''The Transition from Ascetism to Mysticism at the Niddle of the Ninth Century''], in: Studia Islamica 83 (1996), 51\u201370.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.luckynmalone.co.uk/sufism/ Nuri Bibliography]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nuri, Saint}}\n[[Category:Iraqi Sufis]]\n[[Category:Iraqi Sufi saints]]\n[[Category:840 births]]\n[[Category:907 deaths]]\n\n\n{{Sufism-stub}}\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo - title change confirmed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Nuri"}
{"title_page": "JobStreet.com", "text_new": "{{Infobox website\n|  name   = JobStreet\n|  logo   = JobStreet logo.png\n|  type   = \n|  foundation     = 1997\n|  location       = [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]].\n| area_served     = [[Southeast Asia]], [[Japan]], [[India]], [[West Europe]]\n|  key_people     = [[Mark Chang Mun Kee]], CEO<br />Suresh Thiru, COO<br />Albert Wong, CTO <br/>Greg Poarch, CFO\n|  industry       = [[Job search engine|Job Search Engine]]\n|  homepage       = {{URL|http://www.jobstreet.com}}\n|  alexa          = 7094 ({{as of|2016|06|07|alt=7 June 2016}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web|url= http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/jobstreet.com |title= JobStreet.com Site Info | publisher= [[Alexa Internet]] |accessdate= 2016-06-07 }}</ref>\n| revenue          = RM 186.25 million (2014)<ref name=tmi>{{cite web |url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/business/article/jobstreet-posts-bullish-2014-results |title=JobStreet\u2019s pre-tax profit rises to RM1.99 billion from RM84.8 million |accessdate=29 July 2015|year=2014}}</ref>\n| num_users        = 7 million\n}}\n\n'''JobStreet.com''' is a job portal founded in 1997. Founded in [[Malaysia]], it is now Southeast Asia's largest online employment company, according to Forbes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/global/2008/0128/014.html |title=Turning Classifieds Into Cash |publisher=Forbes |date=2008-01-18 |accessdate=2013-10-28}}</ref> It currently serves about 80000 corporate customers and 11 million jobseekers. Even as early as in July 2010, the Group services over 60,000 corporate customers and over 7 million jobseekers.\n\nIt became a public listed entity in 2004 when parent company JobStreet Corporation Berhad was listed on the MESDAQ Market of Bursa Malaysia Securities on 29 Nov 2004. Thereafter, JobStreet.com was listed on the Main Board in October 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mrem.bernama.com/viewsm.php?idm=9872 |title=Bernama Media Relations: Jobstreet.Com Transfers To Main Board |publisher=Mrem.bernama.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> under stock short name, JOBST. JobStreet owns 22.43% of the Taiwanese online employment provider 104 Corporation,<ref>{{cite book|title=JobStreet.com Annual Report 2012|year=2012|publisher=JobStreet.com|page=4|url=http://ir.chartnexus.com/jobstreet/doc/Reports/jobstreet_2012_full.pdf}}</ref> 21.13% of the online marketing technology and services company, Innity Corporation and the automotive portal, [[Autoworld.com.my]].<ref name=\"Jobstreet Corporation Bhd Quarterly Report Notes 31 Mar 2008\">{{cite web|url=http://ir.chartnexus.com/jobstreet/doc/Reports/2008%20Q1%20(Notes).pdf |title=Jobstreet Corporation Bhd Quarterly Report Notes 31 Mar 2008|publisher=Ir.chartnexus.com |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> As of 2016 the total revenue of jobstreet in the Philippines is PHP 2.04 Billion  <ref name=\"bernama1\">{{cite web|url=http://mrem.bernama.com/viewsm.php?idm=15691 |title=BERNAMA MREM Press Release & Asianet |publisher=Mrem.bernama.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref>\n\n==Products and services==\nThe website features a job matching engine named LiNa for jobseekers and a job posting platform named SiVa for employers.\nThe firm also provides other online recruitment products and services such as online recruitment, outsourced human capital service, software as a service (SaaS), e-commerce & e-business and jobseekers' services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ir.chartnexus.com/jobstreet/doc/Reports/jobstreet_2009_full.pdf |title=JobStreet Corporation Berhad : Annual Report 2009 |publisher=Ir.chartnexus.com |accessdate=2013-10-28}}</ref> Classified advertisement also serves as secondary revenue sources for JobStreet.<ref>{{cite book|last=Krishnamurthy,...\u00e9diteur|first=Sandeep|title=Contemporary research in e-marketing.|year=2006|publisher=Idea Group Pub.|location=Hershey (Pa)|isbn=978-1591408246|edition=2|chapter=Job Search at Naukri.com}}</ref>\n\nThe firm also provide resources for jobseekers' career growth. Among these are the JobStreet.com English Language Assessment, the JobStreet.com Resume & Interview assessments,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tools.jobstreet.com/resume-interview-tool/my/ |title=JobStreet.com Malaysia Assessments |publisher=Tools.jobstreet.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> salary reports,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://myjobstreet.jobstreet.com/career-enhancer/basic-salary-report.php?param=|title=JobStreet.com : Salary Report |publisher=Myjobstreet.jobstreet.com |accessdate=2013-10-28}}</ref> and JobStreet Blog,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.jobstreet.com/malaysia/ |title=BlogStreet from JobStreet.com |publisher=Blog.jobstreet.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> (fondly called as BlogStreet, now defunct).<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Zhi Yu|title=Is JobStreet.com Ready for the Next Evolution of Job Market?|url=http://www.zewsays.com/2010/07/is-jobstreetcom-ready-for-next.html|publisher=ZewSays.com|accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nEnvisioned to provide an automated platform for accurately matching employers and jobseekers, JobStreet was founded by [[Mark Chang Mun Kee]] as a spin-off of MOL.com in 1995. The starting capital of JobStreet was reportedly US$2.6 million back then.<ref name=\"forbes1\"/> Prior to that, its parent company MOL AccessPortal was sold to [[Vincent Tan]], the CEO of [[Berjaya Group]] for US$3.2 million.<ref name=\"forbes1\">{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/global/2008/0128/014.html| title=Turning Classifieds Into Cash | date=January 28, 2008 | first=Cris | last=Prystay|publisher=Forbes.com|accessdate=2013-10-28}}</ref> Conservative management<ref>{{cite book|title=Asian Business|year=2001|publisher=Far East Trade Press|page=19|accessdate=|chapter=Online recruitment firm Jobstreet's resume is looking good}}</ref> helped the company sidestep the [[dot-com bubble|dot-com bust]] in 2000s.<ref name=\"forbes1\"/> In 1999, San Francisco venture capital firm Walden International and [[Sumitomo Corporation|Sumitomo Corporation Capital]] Asia made $1.6 million investment in the company and increased its stake in JobStreet to 30% in 2001. Walden catalyzed JobStreet's move from a start-up to a regional major market player. It urged Mark Chang to hire executives with business experience, to expand to other key [[Southeast Asia]] countries and to trim cost.\n\nThe following table summarizes the growth in jobseeker and corporate customers of JobStreet.\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n|-\n!Year!!JobSeekers!!Employers \n|-\n|2003||1,851,000<ref name=\"ir.chartnexus.com\">{{cite web|title=JobStreet Corporation Berhad Annual Report 2006|url=http://ir.chartnexus.com/jobstreet/doc/Reports/jobstreet_2006_full.pdf|accessdate=7 March 2014|pages=2}}</ref> ||NA\n|-\n|2004||2,578,000<ref name=\"ir.chartnexus.com\"/>||15,000<ref>{{cite web|title=JobStreet shows strong growth|url=http://www.jobstreet.co.id/en/aboutus/preleases19.htm|accessdate=7 March 2014|date=25 Nov 2004}}</ref> \n|-\n|2005||3,477,000<ref name=\"ir.chartnexus.com\"/>||2,0000<ref>{{cite web|title=JobStreet reports nine months\u2019 profit of RM11.9 million|url=http://www.jobstreet.co.in/aboutus/preleases21.htm|accessdate=7 March 2014|date=22 Nov 2005}}</ref> \n|-\n|2006||4,168,000<ref name=\"ir.chartnexus.com\"/>||20,000<ref>{{cite web|title=JOBSTREET.COM Wins Best Online Service Provider Award|url=http://www.jobstreet.co.in/aboutus/preleases22.htm|accessdate=7 March 2014|date=23 Jan 2006}}</ref> \n|-\n|2007||5,303,000<ref name=\"http\">{{cite web|title=JobStreet Corporation Berhad Annual Report 2009|url=http://ir.chartnexus.com/jobstreet/doc/Reports/jobstreet_2009_full.pdf|accessdate=7 March 2014|pages=2|year=2009}}</ref>||45,000<ref>{{cite web|title=JobStreet.com delivers a strong 47% jump in profits for 2nd Quarter, 2007|url=http://jp.jobstreet.com/aboutus/preleases6.htm|accessdate=7 March 2014|location=KUALA LUMPUR|date=18 Aug 2007}}</ref> \n|-\n|2008||6,007,000<ref name=\"http\"/>||50,000<ref>{{cite web|title=JobStreet delivers strongest year-end results yet with RM 28.9 million profit|url=http://jp.jobstreet.com/aboutus/preleases9.htm|accessdate=7 March 2014|location=KUALA LUMPUR|date=25 February 2008}}</ref> \n|-\n|2009||7,032,000<ref name=\"http\"/>||50,000<ref>{{cite web|title=JobStreet.com Reports RM7.3 Million Net Profit for Q2 2009|url=http://jp.jobstreet.com/aboutus/preleases14.htm|accessdate=7 March 2014|location=Kuala Lumpur|date=18 Aug 2009}}</ref> \n|-\n|2010||8,298,000||60,000<ref>{{cite web|title=JobStreet.com Reports RM8.7 Million Net Profit for Q1 2010|url=http://www.jobstreet.com.my/aboutus/preleases127.htm|accessdate=7 March 2014|location=KUALA LUMPUR|date=18 May 2010}}</ref> \n|-\n|2011||10,040,000<ref>{{cite web|title=JobStreet Corporation Berhad Annual Report 2011|url=http://ir.chartnexus.com/jobstreet/doc/Reports/jobstreet_2011_full.pdf|accessdate=7 March 2014|pages=7|year=2011}}</ref> ||70,000\n|-\n|2012||11,450,000<ref>{{cite web|title=JobStreet Corporation Berhad Annual Report 2012|url=http://ir.chartnexus.com/jobstreet/doc/Reports/jobstreet_2012_full.pdf|accessdate=7 March 2014|pages=7|year=2012}}</ref>||80,000<ref>{{cite web|title=JobStreet.com Reports RM14.9 Million Net Profit for Q4 2012|url=http://www.jobstreet.com.my/aboutus/jobstreet-reports-14.9million-net-profit-q4-2012.htm|accessdate=7 March 2014|location=KUALA LUMPU|date=19 February 2013}}</ref> \n|}\n\n==Corporate affairs==\nJobStreet.com was selected by Forbes Asia as Best 200 Under a Billion company in 2007 and 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/2008/09/19/asia-best-midcaps-pf-bub08-cz_jg_0918billion_land.html |title=Forbes Asia's Best 200 Under A Billion company |publisher=Forbes.com |date=2008-09-19 |accessdate=2012-07-13}}</ref> In April 2013, it crossed the RM1 billion market capitalization milestone.<ref>{{cite web|first=Karamjit |last=Singh|title=JobStreet hits milestone, crosses RM1bil market cap |url=http://www.digitalnewsasia.com/sizzle-fizzle/jobstreet-hits-milestone-crosses-rm1bil-market-cap|work=Digital News Asia|publisher=Digital News Asia|accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref> \nFollowing its purchase of 10.1% stake in 2008 for $19.3 million<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.livenews.com.au/Articles/2008/09/17/Seek_buys_10_of_Malaysian_JobStreet |title=LIVENEWS.com.au |access-date=2008-10-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080921020509/http://www.livenews.com.au/Articles/2008/09/17/Seek_buys_10_of_Malaysian_JobStreet |archive-date=2008-09-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and another 11.2% stake for RM70.9 million in 2010,<ref>{{cite news|title=Seek ups stake in JobStreet|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/technology/seek-ups-stake-in-jobstreet/story-e6frgakx-1225839201938|accessdate=7 March 2014|newspaper=The Australian|date=10 March 2010}}</ref> SEEK Limited, the Australian internet job recruitment company made a complete takeover in 2014 for RM 1.73 billion <ref>{{cite news|title=Australia's SeekAsia buying JobStreet's business for RM1.73b (Update)|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/Business/Business-News/2014/02/19/Seek-Ltd-to-acquire-online-ops-of-Jobstreet-for-RM1dot73bil/|accessdate=7 March 2014|newspaper=The Star|date=Feb 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=JobStreet to pay almost all of $661 million from sale of online business as dividend |url=http://business.asiaone.com/news/jobstreet-pay-almost-all-661-million-sale-online-business-dividend|accessdate=7 March 2014|newspaper=Asia News Network|date=Feb 20, 2014}}</ref> together with co-investors, [[News Corp (2013\u2013present)|News Corp]], Tiger Global and [[Macquarie Capital]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Moullakis|first=Joyce|title=Behind the deal: SEEK\u2019s Asia push a long game|url=http://www.brw.com.au/p/business/behind_the_deal_seek_asia_push_long_oUukBIrXh3G5NH2DAANc1O|accessdate=7 March 2014|newspaper=BRW|date=24 Feb 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"text-align: center; font-size:95%; width:99%;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Result\n! Reference\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|2015\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Asia Recruitment Awards - Malaysia\n|Best Career Website\n|Gold\n|<ref name=\"2015MYasiarecruitmentawards\">{{cite journal|title=Winners announced: Asia Recruitment Awards Malaysia|url=http://www.humanresourcesonline.net/asia-recruitment-awards/2015/my/2015/05/13/winners-announced-asia-recruitment-awards-malaysia/|work=Human Resources|accessdate=June 7, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|Best Recruitment Innovation\n|Gold\n|<ref name=\"2015MYasiarecruitmentawards\"/>\n|-\n|Asia Recruitment Awards - Singapore\n|Best Career Website\n|Silver\n|<ref name=\"2015SGasiarecruitmentawards\">{{cite journal|title=Winners announced: Asia Recruitment Awards Singapore|url=http://www.humanresourcesonline.net/asia-recruitment-awards/2015/sg/winners/|work=Human Resources|accessdate=June 7, 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Employment website]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jobstreet.com/ Official website]\n\n[[Category:MSC Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Employment websites]]\n[[Category:Malaysian websites]]\n[[Category:Business services companies established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Kuala Lumpur]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Companies formerly listed on MESDAQ Market]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox website\n|  name   = JobStreet\n|  logo   = JobStreet logo.png\n|  type   = \n|  foundation     = 1997\n|  location       = [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]].\n| area_served     = [[Southeast Asia]], [[Japan]], [[India]], [[West Europe]]\n|  key_people     = [[Mark Chang Mun Kee]], CEO<br />Suresh Thiru, COO<br />Albert Wong, CTO <br/>Greg Poarch, CFO\n|  industry       = [[Job search engine|Job Search Engine]]\n|  homepage       = {{URL|http://www.jobstreet.com}}\n|  alexa          = 7094 ({{as of|2016|06|07|alt=7 June 2016}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web|url= http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/job